metadata.title: Boeing-Stearman Model 75
aws::graph::propositions: Boeing-Stearman Model 75 Military and Civilian Evaluation and Orders
The Army Air Corps evaluated the Boeing-Stearman Model 75 in autumn.
The Boeing-Stearman Model 75 was powered by a 225-hp Wright R-760 engine.
The Boeing-Stearman Model 75 was powered by a 225-hp Lycoming R-680 engine.
The Army Air Corps ordered 26 Boeing-Stearman Model 75 aircraft with the Lycoming engine in July 1935.
The Boeing-Stearman Model 75 aircraft with Lycoming engines were designated as PT-13A.
The United States Navy ordered 20 Boeing-Stearman Model 75 aircraft in July 1935.
The Army ordered an additional 50 PT-13A aircraft in August 1936.
The Army ordered 30 more PT-13A aircraft in October 1936.
The Army ordered 28 more PT-13A aircraft in December 1936.
Stearman Aircraft Company received orders for Boeing-Stearman Model 75 primary trainers from the Argentinian Navy.
Stearman Aircraft Company received orders for Boeing-Stearman Model 75 primary trainers from the Philippine Army Air Corps.
Stearman Aircraft Company received orders for Boeing-Stearman Model 75 primary trainers from the Brazilian Air Force.
The Army ordered another 26 PT-13A aircraft in January 1937.
The U.S. government issued Approved Type Certificate No. 743 for the civilian version of the Boeing-Stearman Model 75 on 6 June 1941.

text:
The Army Air Corps evaluated the plane that autumn, powered by a 225-hp Wright R-760 or a 225-hp Lycoming R-680. In July 1935, the Army Air Corps ordered 26 with the Lycoming engine, designated the PT-13A, while the navy ordered an additional 20. In August 1936, the Army ordered an additional 50 PT-13As, followed by another 30 in October, and another 28 in December. Simultaneously, the company received orders for its primary trainer from the Argentinian navy, the Philippine Army Air Corps, and the Brazilian Air Force. In January 1937, the army ordered another 26 PT-13As.
On 6 June 1941, the U.S. government issued Approved Type Certificate No. 743 for the civilian version of the Model 75.
